The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro

 The City Diary

 Police have decided to maintain vigil in plainclothes near pandals in Behala, Regent Park, Kasba, Thakurpukur and the adjacent areas during the Puja. Women constables will also be deployed.

 uperintendent of police (South 24-Parganas) S.N. Gupta said the cops would also try to keep noise pollution in check during the festival. Complaints can be registered by dialling 100.

 o ensure trouble-free festivities, more than 5,000 criminals have been arrested. ?We have identified 18 spots where special assistance booths will be set up,? said Gupta.

 bout 750 NCC cadets and 60 women constables will be on duty on the Puja days.

 Metro Railway will instal four coin-vending machines at Park Street, Esplanade, Tollygunge and Dum Dum stations this week. The machines will provide change for Rs 10 and Rs 20 notes in Re 1 and Rs 2 coins. 

 ccording to the Metro authorities, the machines were procured from Allahabad Bank ?in public interest? and are being installed in front of the ticket counters. The in-built safety mechanism of the machines will reject soiled and torn notes, and paper. 

 The US embassy and consulates-general in Calcutta, Mumbai and Chennai have entered an agreement with VFS (India) Pvt. Ltd. to provide visa applicants from across the country with information, appointments and courier services. 

 he cost for US visa-related services in India has been reduced to Rs 276 (including taxes). An applicant, however, will still have to pay a non-immigration application fee of $100.

 Chief minister Buddhadeb Bhattacharjee felicitated nine Calcuttans for their bravery and honesty, and awarded 48 policemen for their commendable service and contribution to Calcutta Police at the National Library auditorium on Thursday. 

 hile the civilians received a memento and certificate each, the cops were given a medal and cash, ranging from Rs 5,000 to Rs 20,000. In his speech, Bhattacharjee congratulated Seunandan Prasad Yadav, a taxi driver who had returned valuables left in the car by a passenger.

 Students of Jogomaya Devi College will boycott classes on Friday to protest the alleged assault on teachers by a section of the non-teaching staff and outsiders during an altercation on campus on Thursday. There is a difference of opinion between teachers and the non-teaching staff over alleged misappropriation of funds by the principal.

 State finance minister Asim Dasgupta on Thursday inaugurated barracks for constables on the Dum Dum police station premises. A conference room was also inaugurated at the thana.

 Several passengers of a bus on route SD 27 were injured on Thursday morning when they tried to jump off, thinking the vehicle had caught fire. The bus was travelling to Esplanade from Diamond Harbour when smoke started billowing out of the driver?s cabin.

 Pedestrians beat up a youth on Park Street on Thursday evening for teasing a girl. According to police, the incident occurred around 7 pm when the girl and her friend were walking down the road. The youth was handed over to police. 

